  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Urinary iodine concentration (UIC) is the recommended biomarker of iodine status in
      populations. Yet, the influence of climate on UIC remains unclear. Hot climate may reduce
      urine volume and consequently increase UIC independent of iodine status. This could lead to
      an overestimation of population iodine intake, thus masking iodine deficiency in vulnerable
      groups.

      In this longitudinal observational cohort study in women of reproductive age we will collect
      24h and spot urine samples in the summer and winter season. The influence of high temperature
      climates on UIC, measured and estimated urinary iodine excretion will be estimated.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
